                <h2>The Beauty and Challenge of Onyx Countertops</h2>
                <p>Onyx is one of the most visually striking natural stones available for countertops and surfaces. With its luxurious translucent appearance, dramatic veining, and rich depth of color, onyx creates a statement unlike any other material. When backlit, onyx transforms into a glowing work of art that turns kitchens, bathrooms, and living spaces into something truly extraordinary.</p>
                <p>Beyond countertops, onyx is also a popular choice for backsplashes, accent walls, fireplace surrounds, and flooring in high-end residential and commercial projects. Its unique beauty makes it a favorite among designers and homeowners who want their spaces to stand apart.</p>
                <p>However, that beauty comes with responsibility. Onyx is a softer, more porous stone compared to materials like <a href="../kitchen-bath">quartz or granite</a>, which means it requires proper care and attention to maintain its appearance over time. The good news is that with the right cleaning and maintenance routine, your onyx surfaces can look stunning for decades.</p>

                <h2>Step 1: Daily Cleaning with the Right Products</h2>
                <p>The foundation of onyx care starts with how you clean it every day. Because onyx is a porous stone, it can absorb liquids if not properly sealed, which makes your choice of cleaning products critically important.</p>
                <p>The most important rule is to avoid acidic substances at all costs. Vinegar, lemon juice, wine, coffee, and citrus-based cleaners can etch and dull the polished surface of onyx, leaving permanent marks. You should also skip harsh chemical cleaners, bleach, and abrasive scrubbing powders, as these can scratch or damage the stone.</p>
                <p>Instead, use a pH-neutral stone cleaner specifically designed for natural stone surfaces. If you do not have a stone-specific product on hand, a small amount of mild dish soap diluted in warm water works well as an alternative.</p>
                <p>Here are the daily cleaning best practices for onyx:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Use soft microfiber cloths:</strong> Microfiber is gentle enough to clean without scratching the surface. Avoid rough sponges, steel wool, or abrasive pads.</li>
                    <li><strong>Wipe gently, never scrub:</strong> Apply light, even pressure when cleaning. Aggressive scrubbing can wear down the polished finish over time.</li>
                    <li><strong>Blot spills instead of wiping:</strong> When a spill occurs, blot it up immediately with a clean cloth rather than wiping it across the surface. Wiping can spread the liquid and push it into the pores of the stone.</li>
                    <li><strong>Dry the surface after cleaning:</strong> Use a separate dry microfiber cloth to remove any remaining moisture and prevent water spots.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Step 2: Seal Onyx Countertops for Protection</h2>
                <p>Sealing is the single most important step you can take to protect your onyx countertops. A quality stone sealant creates an invisible barrier that prevents liquids, oils, and stains from penetrating the porous surface. Without that protective layer, onyx is highly vulnerable to staining, discoloration, and even structural damage over time.</p>
                <p>For best results, you should reseal your onyx countertops every 6 to 12 months, depending on how heavily the surfaces are used. High-traffic areas like kitchen countertops and bathroom vanities may need more frequent sealing.</p>
                <p>Not sure if your onyx needs resealing? Here is a simple test you can do at home: sprinkle a few drops of water on the surface and wait a few minutes. If the stone darkens where the water sits, the sealant has worn off and it is time to reseal. If the water beads up on the surface without being absorbed, your seal is still intact.</p>
                <p>When applying sealant, follow the product instructions carefully and make sure the surface is completely clean and dry before you begin. Apply the sealant evenly, allow it to penetrate for the recommended time, then buff away any excess with a clean cloth.</p>

                <h2>Step 3: Prevent Heat and Scratch Damage</h2>
                <p>Onyx is a softer natural stone, which means it needs more protection from physical damage than harder materials like quartz or granite. Taking a few simple precautions can prevent scratches, burns, and other damage that would require professional repair.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Always use hot pads and trivets:</strong> Never place hot pots, pans, or baking dishes directly on onyx. The sudden heat can cause thermal shock, leading to cracks, discoloration, or dulling of the surface.</li>
                    <li><strong>Use cutting boards:</strong> Never cut or chop food directly on onyx. Even everyday kitchen knives can scratch the surface. Always use a cutting board to protect the stone.</li>
                    <li><strong>Place felt pads under decorative items:</strong> Vases, candleholders, small appliances, and other objects that sit on the countertop can scratch the surface over time as they are moved around. Adding small felt pads to the bottom of these items provides a protective buffer.</li>
                    <li><strong>Avoid dragging items across the surface:</strong> Lift objects instead of sliding them to prevent scratches and surface wear.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Step 4: Polishing Onyx Countertops</h2>
                <p>Even with the best daily care routine, onyx countertops will develop tiny scratches, dull spots, and surface wear over time. This is completely normal for a natural stone. Polishing restores the smooth, luminous finish that makes onyx so beautiful in the first place.</p>
                <p>Professional polishing is strongly recommended for onyx because of how delicate the stone is. A trained stone care specialist has the tools, products, and expertise to polish onyx without causing damage. The professional polishing process removes minor blemishes and surface imperfections, smooths out light scratches, and enhances the natural glow and depth of the stone.</p>
                <p>For most homeowners, scheduling professional polishing every few years is sufficient to keep onyx looking its absolute best. If your countertops are in a high-traffic area or you notice the surface starting to lose its luster, you may want to schedule polishing more frequently.</p>
                <p>If you are searching for onyx polishing near you, look for a provider who specializes in natural stone care and has specific experience working with onyx. The delicate nature of the stone requires a careful, knowledgeable approach that differs from polishing harder materials like granite.</p>

                <h2>Why Homeowners Love Onyx Despite the Maintenance</h2>
                <p>Given the care requirements, you might wonder why so many homeowners choose onyx for their countertops and surfaces. The answer is simple: nothing else looks like it. Here is what makes onyx worth the extra attention:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>One-of-a-kind elegance:</strong> Every slab of onyx is completely unique. The veining, color variations, and translucent qualities mean that no two installations will ever look the same. Your countertop is truly one of a kind.</li>
                    <li><strong>Translucent and backlit potential:</strong> Onyx is one of the few natural stones that can be backlit, creating a warm, ethereal glow that transforms any space into something magical. Backlit onyx is especially popular for bar tops, bathroom vanities, and accent walls.</li>
                    <li><strong>Dramatic veining and depth:</strong> The bold, sweeping veining patterns in onyx create visual drama that serves as a focal point in any room. Whether you choose honey onyx, green onyx, or white onyx, the effect is always breathtaking.</li>
                    <li><strong>Sets your space apart:</strong> In a world of common countertop materials, onyx immediately elevates a space from ordinary to extraordinary. It is the kind of feature that guests notice and remember.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Browse our <a href="../gallery">project gallery</a> to see examples of premium stone installations and get inspired for your own project.</p>

                <h2>Care Today, Beauty for a Lifetime</h2>
                <p>Onyx countertops are an investment in beauty and craftsmanship. With the right care routine, they will reward you with decades of stunning visual impact. Here is a quick summary of the essential care steps:</p>
                <ol>
                    <li><strong>Clean daily</strong> with a pH-neutral stone cleaner and soft microfiber cloths. Avoid acidic and harsh chemical products.</li>
                    <li><strong>Seal regularly</strong> every 6 to 12 months to maintain a protective barrier against stains and moisture.</li>
                    <li><strong>Use protection</strong> such as trivets, cutting boards, and felt pads to prevent heat damage and scratches.</li>
                    <li><strong>Polish periodically</strong> with a professional stone care specialist to restore the surface and keep it glowing.</li>
                </ol>
